üìñ The Story of Upper Lea

The Upper Lea flows through the Upper Lea (Hertfordshire) catchment, where our eDNA survey sampled 10 sites along its length. Analysis of water samples revealed a rich invertebrate community with 7,316 distinct genetic sequences (ESVs) representing 715 identified species and 266 families.

Compared to other chalk streams surveyed, the Upper Lea shows one of the most biodiverse rivers in the study, ranking #3 of 10. The river supports 15 families of mayflies, stoneflies, and caddisflies (EPT) - key indicators of water quality.

Notable findings include the detection of conservation priority species (Eurasian otter, Water vole) and invasive species requiring management attention.
